==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hurdle
<hw>Hur"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hurdel</ets>, <ets>hirdel</ets>, AS. <ets>hyrdel</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>horde</ets>, OHG. <ets>hurt</ets>, G. <ets>h⟦uum⟧rde</ets> a
hurdle, fold, pen, Icel. <ets>hur<?/</ets> door, Goth.
<ets>ha⟦uacute⟧rds</ets>, L. <ets>cratis</ets> wickerwork, hurdle, Gr.
<?/, Skr. <ets>k<?/t</ets> to spin, <ets>c<?/t</ets> to bind, connect.
⟦root⟧16. Cf. <er>Crate</er>, <er>Grate</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A movable frame of wattled twigs, osiers, or withes and
stakes, or sometimes of iron, used for inclosing land, for folding sheep
and cattle, for gates, etc.; also, in fortification, used as revetments,
and for other purposes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In England, a sled or crate on which criminals were
formerly drawn to the place of execution.</def>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An artificial barrier, variously constructed, over
which men or horses leap in a race.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hurdle race</b></col>, <cd>a race in which artificial
barriers in the form of hurdles, fences, etc., must be
leaped.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hurdle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hurdle
<hw>Hur"dle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hurdleed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hurdleing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To hedge, cover,
make, or inclose with hurdles.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hurdlework</ent>⟦br⟧
